    • Deprecated Classes
      Class
      Description
      com.google.common.collect.ForwardingBlockingDeque
      This class has moved to com.google.common.util.concurrent. Please use ForwardingBlockingDeque instead.
      com.google.common.collect.TreeTraverser
      Use Traverser instead. All instance methods have their equivalent on the result of Traverser.forTree(tree) where tree implements SuccessorsFunction, which has a similar API as TreeTraverser.children(T) or can be the same lambda function as passed into TreeTraverser.using(Function).
    • Deprecated Exception Classes
      Exception Class
      Description
      com.google.common.collect.ComputationException
      This exception is no longer thrown by com.google.common. Previously, it was thrown by MapMaker computing maps. When support for computing maps was removed from MapMaker, it was added to CacheBuilder, which throws ExecutionException, UncheckedExecutionException, and ExecutionError. Any code that is still catching ComputationException may need to be updated to catch some of those types instead. (Note that this type, though deprecated, is not planned to be removed from Guava.)

      com.google.common.base.Throwables.lazyStackTrace(Throwable)
      This method is equivalent to Throwable.getStackTrace() on JDK versions past JDK 8 and on all Android versions. Use Throwable.getStackTrace() directly, or where possible use the java.lang.StackWalker.walk method introduced in JDK 9.
      com.google.common.base.Throwables.lazyStackTraceIsLazy()
      This method always returns false on JDK versions past JDK 8 and on all Android versions.
      com.google.common.base.Throwables.propagate(Throwable)
      To preserve behavior, use throw e or throw new RuntimeException(e) directly, or use a combination of Throwables.throwIfUnchecked(Throwable) and throw new RuntimeException(e). But consider whether users would be better off if your API threw a different type of exception. For background on the deprecation, read Why we deprecated Throwables.propagate.
      com.google.common.base.Throwables.propagateIfInstanceOf(Throwable, Class<X>)
      Use Throwables.throwIfInstanceOf(Throwable, Class), which has the same behavior but rejects null.
      com.google.common.base.Throwables.propagateIfPossible(Throwable)
      Use Throwables.throwIfUnchecked(Throwable), which has the same behavior but rejects null.
      com.google.common.base.Throwables.propagateIfPossible(Throwable, Class<X>)
      Use a combination of Throwables.throwIfInstanceOf(Throwable, Class) and Throwables.throwIfUnchecked(Throwable), which togther provide the same behavior except that they reject null.
      com.google.common.base.Throwables.propagateIfPossible(Throwable, Class<X1>, Class<X2>)
      Use a combination of two calls to Throwables.throwIfInstanceOf(Throwable, Class) and one call to Throwables.throwIfUnchecked(Throwable), which togther provide the same behavior except that they reject null.

      com.google.common.hash.Hasher.hashCode()
      This returns Object.hashCode(); you almost certainly mean to call hash().asInt().
      com.google.common.hash.Hashing.md5()
      If you must interoperate with a system that requires MD5, then use this method, despite its deprecation. But if you can choose your hash function, avoid MD5, which is neither fast nor secure. As of January 2017, we suggest:
      • For security: Hashing.sha256() or a higher-level API.
      • For speed: Hashing.goodFastHash(int), though see its docs for caveats.
      com.google.common.hash.Hashing.murmur3_32()
      This implementation produces incorrect hash values from the HashFunction.hashString(CharSequence, Charset) method if the string contains non-BMP characters. Use Hashing.murmur3_32_fixed() instead.
      com.google.common.hash.Hashing.murmur3_32(int)
      This implementation produces incorrect hash values from the HashFunction.hashString(CharSequence, Charset) method if the string contains non-BMP characters. Use Hashing.murmur3_32_fixed(int) instead.
      com.google.common.hash.Hashing.sha1()
      If you must interoperate with a system that requires SHA-1, then use this method, despite its deprecation. But if you can choose your hash function, avoid SHA-1, which is neither fast nor secure. As of January 2017, we suggest:
      • For security: Hashing.sha256() or a higher-level API.
      • For speed: Hashing.goodFastHash(int), though see its docs for caveats.
      com.google.common.io.ByteArrayDataOutput.writeBytes(String)
      This method is dangerous as it discards the high byte of every character. For UTF-8, use write(s.getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8)).
      com.google.common.io.Files.append(CharSequence, File, Charset)
      Prefer asCharSink(to, charset, FileWriteMode.APPEND).write(from).
      com.google.common.io.Files.copy(File, Charset, Appendable)
      Prefer asCharSource(from, charset).copyTo(to).
      com.google.common.io.Files.createTempDir()
      For Android users, see the Data and File Storage overview to select an appropriate temporary directory (perhaps context.getCacheDir()), and create your own directory under that. (For example, you might use new File(context.getCacheDir(), "directoryname").mkdir(), or, if you need an arbitrary number of temporary directories, you might have to generate multiple directory names in a loop until mkdir() returns true.) For JRE users, prefer Files.createTempDirectory(Path, String, FileAttribute...), transforming it to a File using toFile() if needed. To restrict permissions as this method does, pass PosixFilePermissions.asFileAttribute(PosixFilePermissions.fromString("rwx------")) to your call to createTempDirectory.
      com.google.common.io.Files.hash(File, HashFunction)
      Prefer asByteSource(file).hash(hashFunction).
      com.google.common.io.Files.readBytes(File, ByteProcessor<T>)
      Prefer asByteSource(file).read(processor).
      com.google.common.io.Files.readFirstLine(File, Charset)
      Prefer asCharSource(file, charset).readFirstLine().
      com.google.common.io.Files.readLines(File, Charset, LineProcessor<T>)
      Prefer asCharSource(file, charset).readLines(callback).
      com.google.common.io.Files.toString(File, Charset)
      Prefer asCharSource(file, charset).read().
      com.google.common.io.Files.write(CharSequence, File, Charset)
      Prefer asCharSink(to, charset).write(from).
      com.google.common.io.LittleEndianDataOutputStream.writeBytes(String)
      The semantics of writeBytes(String s) are considered dangerous. Please use LittleEndianDataOutputStream.writeUTF(String s), LittleEndianDataOutputStream.writeChars(String s) or another write method instead.

      com.google.common.util.concurrent.ClosingFuture.eventuallyClosing(ListenableFuture<C>, Executor)
      Creating Futures of closeable types is dangerous in general because the underlying value may never be closed if the Future is canceled after its operation begins. Consider replacing code that creates ListenableFutures of closeable types, including those that pass them to this method, with ClosingFuture.submit(ClosingCallable, Executor) in order to ensure that resources do not leak. Or, to start a pipeline with a ListenableFuture that doesn't create values that should be closed, use ClosingFuture.from(ListenableFuture).
